    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethenedinitrile diamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h1-2H,(H2,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"alanyl glycine equivalent not used\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonyl-glycine dipeptide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to pyruvate-like keto acid pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, magnetite, mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent to vent-margin setting; anoxic; H2-rich; low-temperature chimney precipitates near 40-80C favored for product persistence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation and carbon-fixation-like iron-sulfur chemistry generates reduced carboxylates including pyruvate; extension to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate is a connected but less directly demonstrated homologation step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate formation on FeS systems under hydrothermal conditions is supported by Cody et al. (2000), while vent mineralogy and low-temperature alkaline chimney relevance are supported by White et al. (2015) and Lane & Martin (2012). Extension to threonine's keto precursor is included as a necessary but partially speculative homologation consistent with Huber & Wachtershauser (2006), Muchowska et al. (2019), and Kaur et al. (2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of simple aldehydes from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) cyanide minerals\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system with mineral photocatalytic surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-irradiated surface pool; phosphate-buffer-compatible cyanosulfidic regime; H2S as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN through cyanide photoredox cycling yields formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This directly follows the cyanosulfidic aldehyde-generating chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). TiO2 is included as a plausible co-occurring photocatalytic mineral in UV-exposed pools per Dunn et al. (1981), without replacing the Cu-cyanide photoredox core.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol homologation from glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals and clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic or hot-spring pool; borate stabilization of sugars\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldol/formose-type carbon-carbon bond formation generates glyceraldehyde from lower aldehydes, with borate suppressing uncontrolled rearrangement and stabilizing sugar products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyceraldehyde is a key branch point in Sutherland-type chemistry and aldol/formose chemistry with borate stabilization is consistent with the literature summary and established sugar chemistry; its central role connecting nucleotide and amino-acid precursors is emphasized by Patel et al. (2015) and the branch-point discussion in the research summary. This step is a necessary network connector and moderately inferential rather than directly quantified for the exact substrate pair.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Cu(I) cyanide minerals\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"2 h UV irradiation; H2S reductant; cyanosulfidic surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN, then undergoes photoredox reduction under UV/H2S/Cu-cyanide conditions to yield lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the experimentally demonstrated key step reported by Ritson & Sutherland (2013), who obtained lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin in 19% yield after irradiation. Patel et al. (2015) embeds this chemistry in broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker conditions in anoxic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium, followed by cyanide addition to form 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The lactaldehyde-to-threonine-aminonitrile Strecker sequence is the central validated route described by Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). Mineral surfaces are included for concentration and compatibility with the required surface-agent specification, consistent with clay-mediated concentration in prebiotic pools.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate stabilization and clay concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-exposed or post-photochemical surface pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes Strecker addition with ammonia and cyanide to produce the same threonine aminonitrile branch point.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) specifically identifies a parallel route in which glyceraldehyde plus NH3 and HCN gives the threonine aminonitrile, directly linking RNA-precursor chemistry to amino acid precursor synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN/polymeric nitrile reservoir\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral surfaces under UV and drying-concentration cycles\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN-rich pool; oligomerization reservoir for later hydrolysis products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerizes to diaminomaleonitrile and related polymers that act as a broad precursor reservoir for amino acids upon subsequent processing.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization is a classic prebiotic process and Ruiz-Bermejo et al. (2013) reviewed hydrolysates of HCN polymers yielding 12 proteinogenic amino acids including threonine. DAMN is included as a representative oligomer node.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN oligomer reservoir to amino-acid mixture including threonine and glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable; low to moderate\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis of preformed HCN polymers or residues\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic breakdown of nitrile-rich HCN oligomers releases amino acids as part of a complex product spectrum.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN polymers producing threonine is supported by the review of Ruiz-Bermejo et al. (2013). Product complexity and low selectivity are explicitly acknowledged in that literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs conversion of lactaldehyde to hydantoin intermediate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces with ammonium carbonate-compatible medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonium carbonate / dissolved CO2 conditions; anoxic aqueous pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide and ammonia/carbonate equivalents to form a hydantoin thermodynamic sink.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) experimentally established Bucherer-Bergs-like prebiotic amino acid access through hydantoins for analogous systems, and the deep research report specifically identifies 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin as the expected threonine intermediate from lactaldehyde. This threonine-specific step is literature-anchored but not directly demonstrated, so it remains a necessary extrapolation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable; low to moderate\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis after hydantoin accumulation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ring opening and hydrolysis of the hydantoin yields threonine/allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids is the core outcome of Bucherer-Bergs chemistry as demonstrated by Pulletikurti et al. (2022). The threonine-specific hydrolysis is the expected homologous analogue identified in the research summary and is included as a justified extension.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K to 343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ or Ni\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~8 for Ni/H2 route; alternatively Fe2+ at 70C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The alpha-keto acid undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by reduction to the alpha-amino acid threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids to amino acids is directly demonstrated by Muchowska et al. (2019) using Fe2+ at 70C and by Kaur et al. (2024) using H2/Ni at 22C and pH 8. Threonine's exact precursor 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate was not experimentally tested in those studies, so this reaction is explicitly a literature-supported extrapolation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde to threonine/allothreonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable; likely mild to moderate\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires high glycine concentration or catalytic assistance; thermodynamically unfavorable\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reverse threonine-aldol chemistry forms a C-C bond between glycine-derived and acetaldehyde-derived fragments to give threonine and allothreonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fesko (2016) discusses the reversibility of threonine aldolase chemistry and the unfavorable but conceptually simple condensation of glycine with acetaldehyde to give threonine/allothreonine. No purely prebiotic demonstration of this exact reaction has been reported, so this step is explicitly speculative but included because the literature identifies it as a key structural relationship.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN photoredox chemistry generates acetaldehyde, which is converted through lactaldehyde to the threonine aminonitrile and then threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde direct Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN-derived aldehydes feed sugar homologation to glyceraldehyde, which directly furnishes the threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Lactaldehyde Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde enters hydantoin chemistry before hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymer hydrolysate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Concentrated HCN oligomerizes and on hydrolysis releases threonine among a broader amino acid mixture.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal keto-acid reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal mineral chemistry supplies the keto-acid precursor pool, which is reductively aminated under mild prebiotic conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface lactaldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation supplies reduced carbon pools that can feed surface HCN chemistry and funnel into lactaldehyde-mediated Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface glyceraldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal feedstocks and surface aldehyde chemistry converge on glyceraldehyde, then on the shared threonine aminonitrile hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge analogue through aldehyde pool to lactaldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"The spark-discharge literature indicates in situ production of HCN, NH3, and aldehydes including lactaldehyde precursors; in network form this maps onto the aldehyde pool and lactaldehyde Strecker branch.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge analogue through glyceraldehyde branch\",\n      \"description\": \"A second discharge-compatible route uses the same HCN/ammonia/aldehyde precursor ensemble but channels through glyceraldehyde to the aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycine-acetaldehyde aldol route\",\n      \"description\": \"A conceptually simple but unfavorable route condenses glycine with acetaldehyde to produce threonine/allothreonine directly.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_007\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets threonine through a literature-grounded, cross-environment prebiotic network centered on shared carbon-nitrogen hubs: HCN, acetaldehyde, lactaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, and the threonine aminonitrile. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies reduced C1-C3 feedstocks such as formate, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and concentrating mineral interfaces; surface cyanosulfidic and photochemical chemistry converts HCN into aldehydes and aminonitriles under UV irradiation; biochemical/prebiotic stages complete hydrolysis, reductive amination, and rapid utilization before threonine decomposes. Ten distinct pathways are represented as combinations of experimentally supported routes: cyanosulfidic Strecker entry via lactaldehyde, direct glyceraldehyde Strecker entry, spark-discharge generation of Strecker precursor pools, Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin chemistry, HCN polymer hydrolysate production, speculative-but-literature-anchored aldol/reductive-amination connections, and downstream peptide incorporation. The network explicitly reflects the major literature constraint that threonine is relatively easy to form but thermally fragile, favoring lower-temperature vent margins, UV-exposed pools, and rapid transfer into downstream chemistry.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "