-fixation-like iron-sulfur chemistry generates reduced carboxylates including pyruvate; extension to 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate is a connected but less directly demonstrated homologation step.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate formation on FeS systems under hydrothermal conditions is supported by Cody et al. (2000), while vent mineralogy and low-temperature alkaline chimney relevance are supported by White et al. (2015) and Lane & Martin (2012). Extension to threonine's keto precursor is included as a necessary but partially speculative homologation consistent with Huber & Wachtershauser (2006), Muchowska et al. (2019), and Kaur et al. (2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of simple aldehydes from HCN", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) cyanide minerals", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system with mineral photocatalytic surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated surface pool; phosphate-buffer-compatible cyanosulfidic regime; H2S as reductant"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN through cyanide photoredox cycling yields formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This directly follows the cyanosulfidic aldehyde-generating chemistry of Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). TiO2 is included as a plausible co-occurring photocatalytic mineral in UV-exposed pools per Dunn et al. (1981), without replacing the Cu-cyanide photoredox core."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Aldol homologation from glycolaldehyde and formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals and clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic or hot-spring pool; borate stabilization of sugars"}, "mechanism": "Aldol/formose-type carbon-carbon bond formation generates glyceraldehyde from lower aldehydes, with borate suppressing uncontrolled rearrangement and stabilizing sugar products.", "reasoning": "Glyceraldehyde is a key branch point in Sutherland-type chemistry and aldol/formose chemistry with borate stabilization is consistent with the literature summary and established sugar chemistry; its central role connecting nucleotide and amino-acid precursors is emphasized by Patel et al. (2015) and the branch-point discussion in the research summary. This step is a necessary network connector and moderately inferential rather than directly quantified for the exact substrate pair."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["Cu(I) cyanide minerals", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "2 h UV irradiation; H2S reductant; cyanosulfidic surface pool"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN, then undergoes photoredox reduction under UV/H2S/Cu-cyanide conditions to yield lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the experimentally demonstrated key step reported by Ritson & Sutherland (2013), who obtained lactaldehyde from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin in 19% yield after irradiation. Patel et al. (2015) embeds this chemistry in broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Direct Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (molybdenite/stibnite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous Strecker conditions in anoxic pool"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine/iminium, followed by cyanide addition to form 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "The lactaldehyde-to-threonine-aminonitrile Strecker sequence is the central validated route described by Ritson & Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). Mineral surfaces are included for concentration and compatibility with the required surface-agent specification, consistent with clay-mediated concentration in prebiotic pools."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Direct Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate stabilization and clay concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-exposed or post-photochemical surface pool"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes Strecker addition with ammonia and cyanide to produce the same threonine aminonitrile branch point.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) specifically identifies a parallel route in which glyceraldehyde plus NH3 and HCN gives the threonine aminonitrile, directly linking RNA-precursor chemistry to amino acid precursor synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN/polymeric nitrile reservoir", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surfaces under UV and drying-concentration cycles", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN-rich pool; oligom