lycine equivalents, or concentration mechanisms if retaining it\",\n        \"Avoid treating it as a competitive main route to target accumulation\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.8,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a good, well-connected synthesis network with strong literature alignment around the cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde/Strecker chemistry and a useful set of convergent alternatives. Topologically, the network is dense and connected, with clear hubs at HCN, acetaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile. Convergence is good, especially at lactaldehyde and threonine aminonitrile. Environmental interconnection is present, but weaker than claimed because the hydrothermal chemistry is not as rigorously integrated as the surface chemistry. The major strengths are: strong agreement with Ritson-Sutherland/Patel-style chemistry; inclusion of Bucherer-Bergs and HCN polymer hydrolysate alternatives; explicit recognition of threonine fragility; and multiple routes to common intermediates. The principal weaknesses are: rxn_001 is overly compressed and speculative; several pathways terminate at threonine aminonitrile without explicit hydrolysis to threonine; the spark-discharge pathways are analogical rather than mechanistically represented; and the glycine + acetaldehyde aldol route is too speculative to support strongly. Mineral-agent compliance cannot be fully confirmed from the summarized network because specific minerals are not listed for the individual reactions here; this is a notable schema-level concern given the original requirements. Overall, the network is close to approval quality because the core literature-backed pathways are strong, but confidence is reduced by speculative hydrothermal entries and incomplete explicit target-forming steps in some pathways.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluatio