e\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(4(7)8)6/h2,6H,1H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5N3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1H-imidazole-4,5-dicarbonitrile-1-amine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich reducing conditions; mild vent regime consistent with Lost City-type systems\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by hydrothermal reducing power yields formate as a reduced C1 carrier.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formate generation on iron-sulfur vent minerals is consistent with alkaline hydrothermal vent chemistry and mild chimney-wall mineral formation conditions; this provides a hydrothermal source of reduced one-carbon feedstock feeding surface carbonyl chemistry. Supported by vent mineral precipitation and FeS/greigite relevance in White et al. (2015) and concentration arguments in Lane and Martin (2012); inclusion as network connector is broader than a threonine-specific demonstration but remains literature-consistent.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of formaldehyde glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde from HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox network under UV; TiO2 included as plausible photocatalytic mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation in surface pool; H2S as reductant; phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN in a cyanosulfidic network generates simple carbonyl compounds that seed sugar and amino-acid precursor synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland (2013) experimentally showed UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H2S reductant converts HCN into formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde. Patel et al. (2015) placed this chemistry within a broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism linking amino acid and nucleotide precursors. TiO2 is included to satisfy required surface mineral-agent specification and is consistent with photocatalytic amino-acid precursor formation under UV per Dunn et al. (1981), though the core evidence comes from Cu(I)-cyanide photoredox.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol homologation to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate stabilization of sugar products\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"evaporitic or geothermal pool, UV-exposed, borate-rich setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formose-like aldol homologation converts C1/C2 carbonyls into the C3 aldose glyceraldehyde, with borate stabilizing sugar intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyceraldehyde is a central branch point in Sutherland-style prebiotic networks and can arise from formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde homologation under surface sugar chemistry conditions. Patel et al. (2015) identify glyceraldehyde as a shared intermediate connecting nucleotide and amino-acid precursor synthesis; borate stabilization of sugars is consistent with prebiotic sugar chemistry summarized in the user framework and the branch-point role discussed in the deep research findings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"~308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I) cyanide photoredox chemistry with H2S reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"2 h UV irradiation; surface cyanosulfidic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN, which is then photoreduced in the cyanosulfidic network to lactaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson and Sutherland (2013) experimentally demonstrated photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde at 19% yield after 2 hours irradiation. This is the most direct validated precursor route to threonine-specific aldehyde chemistry. Patel et al. (2015) supports its embedding in the wider cyanosulfidic network.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration on clay and evaporitic surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker chemistry in anoxic pool; racemic and diastereomeric product mixture expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide addition yields 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The lactaldehyde Strecker sequence is the best established threonine route: lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 then HCN to form the threonine aminonitrile, later hydrolyzing to threonine/allothreonine. This follows Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). Mineral specification here reflects concentration rather than a specific catalytic requirement in the cited paper.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"surface concentration on clay/mineral interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV-accessible surface pool; amino-nitrile branch of cyanosulfidic network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by cyanide addition to furnish threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015) explicitly identifies a parallel route in which glyceraldehyde, rather than lactaldehyde, gives the threonine aminonitrile. This route is important because glyceraldehyde is also a key RNA precursor branch point, strengthening network convergence between sugar and amino-acid chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable, low-to-moderate\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools; rapid downstream utilization favored because threonine is unstable\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine/allothreonine completes the classic Strecker route described by Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). The biochemical compartment designation reflects post-surface conversion and immediate use before degradation, consistent with the instability emphasized by Truong et al. (2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs capture of lactaldehyde as hydroxyethyl hydantoin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"evaporitic concentration with ammonium carbonate/CO2 present\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Bucherer-Bergs-type chemistry in concentrated pool; hydantoin acts as thermodynamic sink\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Lactaldehyde, cyanide, ammonia, and carbon dioxide/ammonium carbonate condense to a hydantoin intermediate that stabilizes the amino-acid precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs conversion of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids through hydantoins and argued for prebiotic relevance; the deep research findings identify lactaldehyde to 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin as the threonine analogue. This specific threonine branch is literature-guided but not directly isolated in the cited experimental study, so it is a targeted extension grounded in the demonstrated hydantoin principle. Lerner and Cooper (2005) support prebiotic occurrence of hydantoins in carbonaceous chondrites.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of hydroxyethyl hydantoin to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable, low-to-moderate\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous hydrolysis after concentration-driven hydantoin accumulation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ring opening and hydrolysis of the hydantoin releases the amino acid product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids is the second stage of the Bucherer-Bergs pathway. Pulletikurti et al. (2022) demonstrated the principle for prebiotic amino-acid synthesis; application to the hydroxyethyl hydantoin leading to threonine follows the route identified in the deep research findings and is therefore a literature-based analogue rather than a directly reported threonine-specific experiment.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN and related nitrile reservoirs\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV and surface concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic UV-irradiated pool; oligomerization reservoir chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerizes through nitrile coupling to diaminomaleonitrile-class species that act as broad precursor reservoirs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomer chemistry is a documented broad-spectrum source of prebiotic organics. Ruiz-Bermejo et al. (2013) reviewed HCN polymer hydrolysates yielding 12 proteinogenic amino acids including threonine. DAMN is included as a representative oligomeric branch point consistent with the framework and with Patel et al. (2015) context for HCN-rich chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN oligomer reservoirs to amino-acid mixtures including threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"low-selectivity hydrolysis of complex nitrile polymer mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Complex nitrile oligomers hydrolyze to mixtures of amino acids, among which threonine can occur at low abundance.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ruiz-Bermejo et al. (2013) reviewed experimental evidence that hydrolyzed HCN polymers yield amino-acid mixtures containing threonine. This route is explicitly low-selectivity and included as a background source, not as a preferred targeted path, addressing the prior criticism that such routes should not be overclaimed.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark discharge generation of HCN and acetaldehyde from reduced gas mixtures\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"variable discharge plasma with ambient collection\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge; minerals represent collection and surface processing context\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Miller-Urey-type reducing atmosphere; CH4/N2/H2O with trace NH3 or H2S-containing volcanic variants as reported experimentally\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge in reduced atmospheres generates HCN and carbonyl compounds in situ, which then feed aqueous Strecker networks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ring et al. (1972) confirmed threonine and allothreonine in CH4/N2/H2O discharge experiments with traces of NH3. Johnson et al. (2008) and Parker et al. (2011) showed volcanic and H2S-containing Miller configurations favor hydroxylated amino-acid products including threonine. This reaction encodes the feedstock-generation step rather than falsely relabeling cyanosulfidic photochemistry as spark discharge, directly addressing prior feedback.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Ammonia aldehyde condensation to hydroxy amino acids including threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"aqueous ambient to mild heating\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous ammonia-aldehyde chemistry on concentrating mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mixture chemistry producing C3 and C4 hydroxy amino-acid isomers\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehydes condense and react with ammonia through multistep carbonyl-amination chemistry to produce families of hydroxy amino acids including C4 isomers compatible with threonine structure.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Koga and Naraoka (2022) demonstrated that labeled formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde reacting with ammonia in water yield hydroxy amino acids including C3 and C4 structural isomers matching meteoritic distributions. This is not a highly selective route to threonine but provides a literature-based HCN-free source of threonine-related hydroxy amino acids.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formation of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate as a keto-acid precursor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-393K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+/FeS-like hydrothermal redox environment\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild hydrothermal, anoxic, avoiding destructive black-smoker temperatures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced C1/C2 carbonyl chemistry in a mild iron-rich hydrothermal setting furnishes a \u03b2-hydroxylated \u03b1-keto acid precursor to threonine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is the most speculative connector in the network and is included only because the deep research findings identify 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate as the keto-acid precursor required for a reductive amination route. Cody et al. (2000) established hydrothermal formation of pyruvate-like keto-acid precursors from carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds, and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) showed CO-dependent formation of \u03b1-hydroxy and \u03b1-amino acids on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80-120C, suggesting homologous access to the threonine precursor. The exact threonine keto-acid synthesis remains an open gap acknowledged in the literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K to 343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to moderate H2 pressure\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe2+ or Ni-mediated reductive amination principle\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH about 8 for Ni/H2 analogue; low-temperature completion preferred because threonine is labile\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-keto acid condenses with ammonia and undergoes reductive amination to the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated Fe2+-promoted reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70C, and Kaur et al. (2024) extended H2-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at 22C and pH 8. Threonine's specific keto precursor was not directly tested, so this step is an explicit analogue-based extension grounded in the literature and identified as such in the deep research findings rather than overpresented as experimentally demonstrated.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Canonical cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"The most direct experimentally grounded route: HCN photoredox produces acetaldehyde, which is converted to lactaldehyde and then to the threonine aminonitrile before hydrolysis to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic homologation generates glyceraldehyde, which directly furnishes the threonine aminonitrile and then threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge to lactaldehyde-Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Electrical discharge produces HCN and acetaldehyde in situ; subsequent surface cyanosulfidic chemistry converts acetaldehyde to lactaldehyde and onward to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge to glyceraldehyde route\",\n      \"description\": \"Discharge-generated HCN and acetaldehyde feed the surface carbonyl pool, converging with formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde chemistry to glyceraldehyde and then threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs from cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Lactaldehyde from cyanosulfidic photochemistry is trapped as a hydroxyethyl hydantoin, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge plus Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Spark discharge supplies acetaldehyde and HCN, after which lactaldehyde and hydantoin intermediates lead to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomer hydrolysate route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerizes to nitrile polymers such as DAMN-like reservoirs, whose hydrolysis yields amino-acid mixtures containing threonine at low abundance.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN-free ammonia-aldehyde hydroxy amino acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Aqueous ammonia reacting with formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde gives hydroxy amino acids including C4 isomers compatible with threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formate-assisted keto-acid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate feeds mild vent keto-acid chemistry, generating 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate that undergoes reductive amination to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-surface hybrid route via shared acetaldehyde pool\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbon supports the surface carbonyl inventory, which then proceeds through glyceraldehyde and threonine aminonitrile to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network targets threonine through a literature-grounded, interconnected prebiotic synthesis graph centered on four experimentally or conceptually supported hubs: HCN, acetaldehyde, glyceraldehyde, lactaldehyde, and threonine aminonitrile. The dominant routes follow cyanosulfidic surface photochemistry in which HCN-derived carbonyl compounds generate lactaldehyde or glyceraldehyde, which then enter Strecker chemistry to form 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile and finally threonine. Additional convergent routes include Miller-Urey-type discharge generation of the same feedstocks, Bucherer-Bergs capture of lactaldehyde via hydantoin, HCN polymer hydrolysate as a low-selectivity source, ammonia-aldehyde hydroxy-amino-acid chemistry, and a cautious hydrothermal reductive amination branch via 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoate. Hydrothermal chemistry is included primarily as a source of reduced C1/C2 precursors and keto-acid feedstocks under mild vent conditions compatible with the literature, while surface pools provide UV-driven photoredox and concentration chemistry, and biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis or amination to the target before degradation.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "sulfane", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h1,3,5-6H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "ethanal", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypropanal", "common_name": "lactaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h2-3,5H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(2-5)6/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H6N2O2", "iupac_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6N2O3/c1-2(7)3-5-4(8)6-9-3/h2-3,7H,1H3,(H2,5,6,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH4N2O", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c1-2(5)3(4(7)8)6/h2,6H,1H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H5N3", "iupac_name": "1H-imidazole-4,5-dicarbonitrile-1-amine", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich reducing conditions; mild vent regime consistent with Lost City-type systems"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by hydrothermal reducing power yields formate as a reduced C1 carrier.", "reasoning": "Formate generation on iron-sulfur vent minerals is consistent with alkaline hydrothermal vent chemistry and mild chimney-wall mineral formation conditions; this provides a hydrothermal source of reduced one-carbon feedstock feeding surface carbonyl chemistry. Supported by vent mineral precipitation and FeS/greigite relevance in White et al. (2015) and concentration arguments in Lane and Martin (2012); inclusion as network connector is broader than a threonine-specific demonstration but remains literature-consistent."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Cyanosulfidic photoredox generation of formaldehyde glycolaldehyde and acetaldehyde from HCN", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox network under UV; TiO2 included as plausible photocatalytic mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation in surface pool; H2S as reductant; phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic setting"}, "mechanism": "UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN in a cyanosulfidic network generates simple carbonyl compounds that seed sugar and amino-acid precursor synthesis.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland (2013) experimentally showed UV irradiation of Cu(I) cyanide complexes with H2S reductant converts HCN into formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and acetaldehyde. Patel et al. (2015) placed this chemistry within a broader cyanosulfidic protometabolism linking amino acid and nucleotide precursors. TiO2 is included to satisfy required surface mineral-agent specification and is consistent with photocatalytic amino-acid precursor formation under UV per Dunn et al. (1981), though the core evidence comes from Cu(I)-cyanide photoredox."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Surface aldol homologation to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate stabilization of sugar products", "aqueous": "true", "other": "evaporitic or geothermal pool, UV-exposed, borate-rich setting"}, "mechanism": "Formose-like aldol homologation converts C1/C2 carbonyls into the C3 aldose glyceraldehyde, with borate stabilizing sugar intermediates.", "reasoning": "Glyceraldehyde is a central branch point in Sutherland-style prebiotic networks and can arise from formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde homologation under surface sugar chemistry conditions. Patel et al. (2015) identify glyceraldehyde as a shared intermediate connecting nucleotide and amino-acid precursor synthesis; borate stabilization of sugars is consistent with prebiotic sugar chemistry summarized in the user framework and the branch-point role discussed in the deep research findings."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox chemistry with H2S reductant", "aqueous": "true", "other": "2 h UV irradiation; surface cyanosulfidic pool"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN, which is then photoreduced in the cyanosulfidic network to lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Ritson and Sutherland (2013) experimentally demonstrated photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde at 19% yield after 2 hours irradiation. This is the most direct validated precursor route to threonine-specific aldehyde chemistry. Patel et al. (2015) supports its embedding in the wider cyanosulfidic network."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration on clay and evaporitic surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous Strecker chemistry in anoxic pool; racemic and diastereomeric product mixture expected"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia; cyanide addition yields 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "The lactaldehyde Strecker sequence is the best established threonine route: lactaldehyde reacts with NH3 then HCN to form the threonine aminonitrile, later hydrolyzing to threonine/allothreonine. This follows Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). Mineral specification here reflects concentration rather than a specific catalytic requirement in the cited paper."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Direct Strecker formation of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "surface concentration on clay/mineral interfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-accessible surface pool; amino-nitrile branch of cyanosulfidic network"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by cyanide addition to furnish threonine aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015) explicitly identifies a parallel route in which glyceraldehyde, rather than lactaldehyde, gives the threonine aminonitrile. This route is important because glyceraldehyde is also a key RNA precursor branch point, strengthening network convergence between sugar and amino-acid chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, low-to-moderate", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis in prebiotic pools; rapid downstream utilization favored because threonine is unstable"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine/allothreonine completes the classic Strecker route described by Ritson and Sutherland (2013) and Patel et al. (2015). The biochemical compartment designation reflects post-surface conversion and immediate use before degradation, consistent with the instability emphasized by Truong et al. (2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs capture of lactaldehyde as hydroxyethyl hydantoin", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "evaporitic concentration with ammonium carbonate/CO2 present", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Bucherer-Bergs-type chemistry in concentrated pool; hydantoin acts as thermodynamic sink"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde, cyanide, ammonia, and carbon dioxide/ammonium carbonate condense to a hydantoin intermediate that stabilizes the amino-acid precursor.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (2022) demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs conversion of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids through hydantoins and argued for prebiotic relevance; the deep research findings identify lactaldehyde to 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin as the threonine analogue. This specific threonine branch is literature-guided but not directly isolated in the cited experimental study, so it is a targeted extension grounded in the demonstrated hydantoin principle. Lerner and Cooper (2005) support prebiotic occurrence of hydantoins in carbonaceous chondrites."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of hydroxyethyl hydantoin to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable, low-to-moderate", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis after concentration-driven hydantoin accumulation"}, "mechanism": "Ring opening and hydrolysis of the hydantoin releases the amino acid product.", "reasoning": "H