3 and C4 hydroxy amino-acid isomers"}, "mechanism": "Aldehydes condense and react with ammonia through multistep carbonyl-amination chemistry to produce families of hydroxy amino acids including C4 isomers compatible with threonine structure.", "reasoning": "Koga and Naraoka (2022) demonstrated that labeled formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and glycolaldehyde reacting with ammonia in water yield hydroxy amino acids including C3 and C4 structural isomers matching meteoritic distributions. This is not a highly selective route to threonine but provides a literature-based HCN-free source of threonine-related hydroxy amino acids."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrothermal formation of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate as a keto-acid precursor", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_008", "mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-393K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe2+/FeS-like hydrothermal redox environment", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild hydrothermal, anoxic, avoiding destructive black-smoker temperatures"}, "mechanism": "Reduced C1/C2 carbonyl chemistry in a mild iron-rich hydrothermal setting furnishes a \u03b2-hydroxylated \u03b1-keto acid precursor to threonine.", "reasoning": "This step is the most speculative connector in the network and is included only because the deep research findings identify 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate as the keto-acid precursor required for a reductive amination route. Cody et al. (2000) established hydrothermal formation of pyruvate-like keto-acid precursors from carbonylated iron-sulfur compounds, and Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2006) showed CO-dependent formation of \u03b1-hydroxy and \u03b1-amino acids on Ni-Fe precipitates at 80-120C, suggesting homologous access to the threonine precursor. The exact threonine keto-acid synthesis remains an open gap acknowledged in the literature."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Reductive amination of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K to 343K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate H2 pressure", "catalyst": "Fe2+ or Ni-mediated reductive amination principle", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH about 8 for Ni/H2 analogue; low-temperature completion preferred because threonine is labile"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-keto acid condenses with ammonia and undergoes reductive amination to the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated Fe2+-promoted reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids at 70C, and Kaur et al. (2024) extended H2-driven reductive amination over nickel catalysts at 22C and pH 8. Threonine's specific keto precursor was not directly tested, so this step is an explicit analogue-based extension grounded in the literature and identified as such in the deep research findings rather than overpresented as experimentally demonstrated."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical cyanosulfidic lactaldehyde-Strecker route", "description": "The most direct experimentally grounded route: HCN photoredox produces acetaldehyde, which is converted to lactaldehyde and then to the threonine aminonitrile before hydrolysis to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Glyceraldehyde Strecker route", "description": "Cyanosulfidic homologation generates glyceraldehyde, which directly furnishes the threonine aminonitrile and then threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Spark-discharge to lactaldehyde-Strecker route", "description": "Electrical discharge produces HCN and acetaldehyde in situ; subsequent surface cyanosulfidic chemistry converts acetaldehyde 