rsion of formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia to threonine as a discrete target-producing step.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_013\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Represent this as a low-selectivity source of hydroxy amino acid isomers rather than direct threonine production\",\n        \"Add uncertainty explicitly and avoid treating it as equivalent in confidence to Strecker-based routes\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.4,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.58\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.5,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.55,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.67,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.56,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.53,\n      \"feedback\": \"This branch is the least literature-grounded among the named target-oriented routes. Formate generation in hydrothermal settings is plausible, but specific formation of 2-oxo-3-hydroxybutyrate from formate, acetaldehyde, and CO2 is not established in the provided literature. Reductive amination of the corresponding keto acid to threonine is conceptually supported by analog studies, but remains untested for this substrate.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_014\",\n        \"rxn_015\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Label the entire keto-acid branch as speculative\",\n        \"Avoid presenting rxn_014 as literature-grounded unless a direct study is cited\",\n        \"If retained, use milder Lost City-type vent conditions and explicit Fe2+/Ni catalysis consistent with the literature\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.4,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.92\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.