central to ribonucleotide synthesis, and glyceraldehyde is specifically identified in the report as a direct entry point to threonine aminonitrile. Borate minerals are included because they stabilize sugars and related aldehydes in surface environments (Patel et al., 2015; de Marcellus et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_004", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (Cu(I) cyanide photoredox system)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "~308K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I) cyanide photoredox chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "2 h UV irradiation; H2S reductant; reported 19% lactaldehyde yield from acetaldehyde cyanohydrin"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde first forms its cyanohydrin with HCN, then UV photoreduction converts that intermediate to lactaldehyde.", "reasoning": "This is the key experimentally demonstrated threonine-specific precursor step. Ritson and Sutherland reported photoreduction of acetaldehyde cyanohydrin to lactaldehyde in 19% yield after 2 h irradiation under cyanosulfidic conditions. TiO2 is added as a plausible mineral photocatalytic support in UV-exposed pools without changing the core literature route (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface concentration and cyanide activation", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous Strecker conditions in evaporitic or photochemical pool; racemic, diastereomeric aminonitrile expected"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde forms an imine with ammonia, followed by cyanide addition to generate 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile.", "reasoning": "The report identifies this as the best-characterized route to the threonine aminonitrile and notes classic Strecker conversion of lactaldehyde with NH3 and HCN. Montmorillonite is used here as a plausible concentrating surface in pools, while sulfide minerals are compatible with cyanosulfidic settings (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Direct Strecker synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration with borate-stabilized aldehyde", "aqueous": "true", "other": "surface pool chemistry; direct amino acid precursor branch from RNA precursor aldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine and then with cyanide to produce threonine aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. identified glyceraldehyde as a parallel route to the threonine aminonitrile and as a branch point connecting RNA and amino acid precursor chemistry. Borate is included because it stabilizes sugar aldehydes in surface settings (Patel et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis in pools, brines, or interfaces; threonine/allothreonine racemic mixture expected"}, "mechanism": "Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide-like intermediates to the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the threonine aminonitrile to threonine/allothreonine is the terminal step implied in Strecker chemistry and explicitly described in the deep report. Mild conditions are favored because threonine is thermally and hydrolytically fragile (Ritson & Sutherland, 2013; Truong et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin formation from lactaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration in evaporitic pools", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonium carbonate present; hydantoin acts as thermodynamic sink"}, "mechanism": "Lactaldehyde reacts with cyanide and ammonium carbonate to form a hydantoin intermediate that sequesters the amino acid precursor in a more stable cyclic form.", "reasoning": "The report identifies the Bucherer-Bergs route as a thermodynamically favorable alternative to direct Strecker chemistry and specifically proposes 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin as the threonine precursor from lactaldehyde. Mineral concentration in surface pools is added to satisfy environmental realism (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; Lerner & Cooper, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of 5-(1-hydroxyethyl)hydantoin to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis after concentration-release cycles"}, "mechanism": "Ring-opening and hydrolysis of the hydantoin releases the amino acid product.", "reasoning": "Hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids is the defining second stage of the Bucherer-Bergs pathway and provides a route to threonine from the lactaldehyde-derived hydantoin. This path is grounded in the demonstrated prebiotic amino-acid hydantoin chemistry of Pulletikurti et al. and the meteoritic occurrence of hydantoins (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; Lerner & Cooper, 2005)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Spark-discharge reservoir synthesis of HCN, ammonia, acetaldehyde, and glycine", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_002", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_008", "mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "electrical discharge with hot-water mist; bulk collection near ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "spark discharge energy with condensation into aqueous reservoir", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S/H2O-type discharge atmospheres; racemic abiotic products; aldehydes and amino acids collected in aqueous phase"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates reactive radicals and nitriles in the gas phase, which collapse into an aqueous reservoir containing HCN, NH3, aldehydes, and amino acids including glycine and threonine precursors.", "reasoning": "Ring et al. first confirmed threonine/allothreonine in discharge products, and Parker et al. showed H2S-containing Miller samples produce a broader amino acid suite including threonine. This reaction is represented explicitly as a precursor-reservoir step rather than incorrectly mapping spark chemistry onto cyanosulfidic photochemistry (Ring et al., 1972; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycine and acetaldehyde to threonine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "requires high glycine concentration or catalytic assistance; low-yield and thermodynamically unfavorable; forms threonine and allothreonine"}, "mechanism": "Reverse of threonine aldol cleavage: C-C bond formation between glycine-derived nucleophile and acetaldehyde gives beta-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid products.", "reasoning": "This route 